[[Image:Ritratto femminile - MC 428 - Musei Capitolini (2).JPG|thumb|Portrait of woman in Pavonazzo marble, Roman artwork - [[Capitoline Museums]] in [[Rome]].]]
[[File:DacePavInfArcoCost.jpg|thumb|Statue in "pavonazzetto" (Docimaean) marble (lower part) in the court of the Conservatori Palace in the Capitoline Museums. This sculpture was on the [[Arch of Constantine]]; it was removed in the 18th century because of damage and replaced by a copy in white marble. Previously, it was in the [[Forum of Trajan]].]]
'''Pavonazzetto marble''' also known as '''Docimaean marble''' or '''Synnadic marble''',<ref name="Strabo">{{cite book|author=Strabo|title=Geography|url=http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0198%3Abook%3D9%3Achapter%3D5%3Asection%3D16}} "Book 9, chapter 5, section 16"</ref> is a white marble originally from [[Docimium]], or modern Iscehisar, Turkey. <ref name="Erica">{{cite book|author=Erica Highes|title=Meaning and λόγος: Proceedings from the Early Professional Interdisciplinary|url=https://books.google.be/books?id=a_WmBgAAQBAJ&dq=pavonazzetto+origin&hl=nl&source=gbs_navlinks_s |year=2013|page=29|publisher=University of Liverpool}}</ref><ref name="Elise A.">{{cite book|author=Elise A. Friedland|title=The Oxford Handbook of Roman Sculpture|url=https://books.google.be/books?id=ph95BgAAQBAJ&dq=belli+pasqua+pavonazzetto&hl=nl&source=gbs_navlinks_s|page=181|year=2015}}</ref>
The name derives from the Italian word for [[peacock]] (pavone). "In natural stone trade, Pavonazzo is often simply called a Marble."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.graniteland.com/stone/pavonazzo |title=Pavonazzo - a white Marble from Italy |publisher=Graniteland.com |date=2012-09-11 |accessdate=2012-12-20}}</ref> It is one of the many varieties of [[Carrara marble]], distinguished by black/gray-veined white marble.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.es.pavonazzo.italy.marble.stoneinfo.us/ |title=Stone Info &#124; Granite Marble |publisher=Es.pavonazzo.italy.marble.stoneinfo.us |date= |accessdate=2012-12-20}}</ref> Also referred to as "pavonazzetto", and distinguished as: #Various red and purplish marbles and [[breccias]]. #A marble, used by the ancient Romans, characterized by very irregular veins of dark red with bluish and yellowish tints.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.answers.com/topic/pavonazzo-pavonazzeto-1 |title=pavonazzo, pavonazzeto: Information from |publisher=Answers.com |date= |accessdate=2012-12-20}}</ref>
The marble has been used in Rome since the Augustan age, when large-scale quarrying began at Docimium, and columns of it were used in the [[House of Augustus]], as well as in the [[Temple of Mars Ultor]], which also had pavonazzo floor tiles in the cella. Pavonazzetto statues of kneeling Phrygian barbarians existed in the [[Basilica Aemilia]] and [[Horti Sallustiani]]. [[Sperlonga sculptures|Giant statue groups]] carved from Docimaean marble were discovered at [[Sperlonga#Villa_of_Tiberius|Tiberius's Villa in Sperlonga]]. Pavonazzetto was not widely or extensively used before the Roman period; there is no evidence of it in circulation before the last two decades B.C.<ref>Matthias Bruno, et al. “The Docimium Marble Sculptures of the Grotto of Tiberius at Sperlonga.” ''American Journal of Archaeology'', vol. 119, no. 3, 2015, pp. 375–394.</ref> Later it was used in Rome in [[Trajan's Markets]] and for the Memoria Petri, the [[tomb of Saint Peter]] and internationally in the influential Baroque Revival-style historic buildings the [[Church of St. Ignatius Loyola (New York City)|Church of St. Ignatius Loyola]], in [[New York City]], and [[Belfast City Hall]] in [[Belfast, Northern Ireland]].
